<div id="review_3586081505" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3586081505" />
    <a title="Brad Lyerla" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4384303-brad-lyerla"><img alt="Brad Lyerla" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620760804p2/4384303.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3586081505?book_show_action=true">Apr 28, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brad Lyerla" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brad Lyerla" href="/user/show/4384303-brad-lyerla">Brad Lyerla</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780226500362" href="/book/show/167924.Discourses_on_Livy">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3586081505" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4365216371183718243">The Discourses is a very fine read. In it, Machiavelli teaches that passions always have and always will dominate politics. Thus, rationality will rarely win the day in even the most enlightened republic. Sometimes other means must be employed to sustain the continued success of a regime.<br/><br/>Like in his more famous book, THE PRINCE, but with a more sophisticated discussion, Machiavelli defends the perogative of a republic to bend to necessity. He offers examples of how and when to bend to necessity </span>
  <span id="freeText4365216371183718243" style="display:none">The Discourses is a very fine read. In it, Machiavelli teaches that passions always have and always will dominate politics. Thus, rationality will rarely win the day in even the most enlightened republic. Sometimes other means must be employed to sustain the continued success of a regime.<br /><br />Like in his more famous book, THE PRINCE, but with a more sophisticated discussion, Machiavelli defends the perogative of a republic to bend to necessity. He offers examples of how and when to bend to necessity by citing anecdotes plucked from history. That history is mostly Roman, but the histories of Greece, Venice, Florence and the Papal States also supply lessons supporting Machiavelli‚Äôs arguments. To a limited extent, he goes even further and suggests patterns of problems that can arise in the political life of a republic. But to the extent this theme can be found in the DISCOURSES, it is pre-scientific and not greatly enlightening. <br /><br />It is noteworthy that in THE DISCOURSES Machievelli expresses a strong preference for republican over aristocratic or dictatorial politics. Republics endure more successfully, in his view. This was a bit unexpected for a reader like me who was familiar only with THE PRINCE.<br /><br />The disappointment for me in the DISCOURSES is that Machiavelli offers no principled way to distinguish between ‚Äúbending to necessity‚Äù and mere expediency. It may be that he believes that there is no universal principle. His many examples illustrate that circumstances are too varied and factually complex to be organized into rules. Thus, politics is an art, not a philosophy or science. The most talented politicians will know when to act undemocratically in order to save the republic like a great artist knows how to create a work of art. And they will understand that undemocratic behaviors are exceptions and should be limited.<br /><br />Of course, Machiavelli‚Äôs discussion is far removed and of diluted relevance to our political life today, at least our political life in the western democracies. Machiavelli predates and does not anticipate the invention of ‚Äúthe rule of law‚Äù. That invention changed the entire conversation. <br /><br />As for Machiavelli‚Äôs relevance to authoritarian regimes today, he would not be a fan. That may come as a surprise to some readers. Generally, Machiavelli does not like dictators, even as he defends situational use of dictatorial practices. Today‚Äôs authoritarian regimes do not understand that resort to dictatorial practices, though unavoidable at times, should be sparing and rare.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4365216371183718243" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


