<div id="review_2718039269" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2718039269" />
    <a title="Kerem" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5317831-kerem"><img alt="Kerem" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1367764785p2/5317831.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2718039269?book_show_action=true">Jul 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kerem" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kerem" href="/user/show/5317831-kerem">Kerem</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2718039269" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer678090104420653843">Principality, Aristocracy, democracy... These &quot;good&quot; ways of government can easily turn into their relevant &quot;bad&quot; ways, tranny, oligarchy, anarchy. Machiavelli states this quite early in the book and in a very clear fashion, and builds up from there his 500+ pages of discourses. Though the book is different from the Prince that its focus is rather republic than principality (and that it&apos;s significantly longer), his overall writing style of an instruction manual and his extremely rational approac</span>
  <span id="freeText678090104420653843" style="display:none">Principality, Aristocracy, democracy... These "good" ways of government can easily turn into their relevant "bad" ways, tranny, oligarchy, anarchy. Machiavelli states this quite early in the book and in a very clear fashion, and builds up from there his 500+ pages of discourses. Though the book is different from the Prince that its focus is rather republic than principality (and that it's significantly longer), his overall writing style of an instruction manual and his extremely rational approach is the same. Overall a very insightful book, even if at times you wonder about the value of some specific discourses (after all 500 years have passed since then and you're likely not interested in whether you should use cavalry in your army or not.) Certainly a 4.5 star at least...</span>
  <a data-text-id="678090104420653843" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
