<div id="review_116630891" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/116630891" />
    <a title="David Nichols" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/655936-david-nichols"><img alt="David Nichols" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1526267895p2/655936.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/116630891?book_show_action=true">Aug 13, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David Nichols" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David Nichols" href="/user/show/655936-david-nichols">David Nichols</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/655936-david-nichols?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/655936-david-nichols?shelf=classics-early-modern">classics-early-modern</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer116630891" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12392200712973100565">I was assigned to read several excerpts from this lesser-known Machiavelli work in college, but didn&apos;t get around to reading the whole thing until I was in my forties. Here&apos;s what I wrote in my journal when I finished it: &quot;Most important insight: that the strength of a republic lies in the diversity of talents it can apply to public problems.&quot; That&apos;s counter-intuitive for a late-medieval European raised to believe in the God-given superiority of kings and princes, but, then, Machiavelli was an e</span>
  <span id="freeText12392200712973100565" style="display:none">I was assigned to read several excerpts from this lesser-known Machiavelli work in college, but didn't get around to reading the whole thing until I was in my forties. Here's what I wrote in my journal when I finished it: "Most important insight: that the strength of a republic lies in the diversity of talents it can apply to public problems." That's counter-intuitive for a late-medieval European raised to believe in the God-given superiority of kings and princes, but, then, Machiavelli was an educated man who grew up in a world of city-states, some of them actual republics. <br /><br />Reading this in college history and poli sci classes, I was encouraged to think of Machiavelli's observations about corruption: that republics become corrupt when they forget their first principles, and that one can restore strength and virtue to them by restoring those principles. A foreign invasion can sometimes do the trick, but it is better to have laws and special officials (tribunes, judges) to renew the state from within. This demonstrates Machiavelli's immersion in the intellectual world of the Renaissance, whose artists and scholars believed that reviving Classical Rome would restore the vigor of their own society. <br /><br />Classical restorationism remained an attractive idea for republicans down to the late eighteenth century, and there is still a trace of it in American political thought, though some conservative Americans would prefer to revive the era of the Hebrew patriarchs rather than that of the Roman consuls. Machiavelli would find this slightly bizarre. But, then, he would find many things about our century unintelligible.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12392200712973100565" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


