    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1685919208" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1685919208" />
    <a title="Peter Aronson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7487616-peter-aronson"><img alt="Peter Aronson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1443852080p2/7487616.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1685919208?book_show_action=true">Jul 02, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Peter Aronson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Peter Aronson" href="/user/show/7487616-peter-aronson">Peter Aronson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780199555550" href="/book/show/6160974-discourses-on-livy">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1685919208" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14150306948648341581">The Discourses, which started as a commentary on Livy&apos;s History of Rome, became something broader. It is known as Machiavelli&apos;s pro-republic book, and it is, but it is important to realize that he did not have a modern concept of a republic -- to him, a republic meant a city state with a republican form of government (a mix of autocracy, aristocracy and democracy). He had no real concept the modern, nation-scale republic. While this book might have been influential with later founders of republi</span>
  <span id="freeText14150306948648341581" style="display:none">The Discourses, which started as a commentary on Livy's History of Rome, became something broader. It is known as Machiavelli's pro-republic book, and it is, but it is important to realize that he did not have a modern concept of a republic -- to him, a republic meant a city state with a republican form of government (a mix of autocracy, aristocracy and democracy). He had no real concept the modern, nation-scale republic. While this book might have been influential with later founders of republics, most of Machiavelli's principles and concerns would not really scale past the city-state. <br /><br />Machiavelli is pro-republic here, be he is still Machiavelli, practical to a fault, with little interest in matters of principle. He favors republics as he things they generally work better than principalities, not because they are good in and of their self. He also has a tendency (common in his day) to over-idealize the Roman Republic, finding it the best model in everything, even in his day.<br /><br />(Self-assigned homework note: I read the first 10 books of Livy as preparation for reading this book; while they were worthwhile reading for their own sake, I'm not really sure I needed to. Oh, they did add some additional dimension to the Discourses, but Machiavelli's lessons are not really Livy's lessons and his thoughts are clear enough on their own. If you <i>are</i> going to prepare this way, it is probably worthwhile to also read Livy's history of the Second Punic War, as it is referenced as much as the first 10 books.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="14150306948648341581" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

