<div id="review_1834388236" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1834388236" />
    <a title="Arthur Bregondo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42879483-arthur-bregondo"><img alt="Arthur Bregondo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1483627598p2/42879483.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1834388236?book_show_action=true">Dec 23, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Arthur Bregondo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Arthur Bregondo" href="/user/show/42879483-arthur-bregondo">Arthur Bregondo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer1834388236&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1834388236" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6446479379011433800">It was a struggle reading The Discourses but that struggle can be mitigated if you have some context of politics and if you keep in mind the relevance of the elements of: necessity, virtue, and fortune. Book I and II is fun to read its like reading Aristotle&apos;s The Politics and Jean-Jacques Rousseau at the same time, but when it came to Book III I found it to be perfunctory and somehow I felt this itch to rush Book III, I am really not a fan of history especially when its all about wars, plebs in</span>
  <span id="freeText6446479379011433800" style="display:none">It was a struggle reading The Discourses but that struggle can be mitigated if you have some context of politics and if you keep in mind the relevance of the elements of: necessity, virtue, and fortune. Book I and II is fun to read its like reading Aristotle's The Politics and Jean-Jacques Rousseau at the same time, but when it came to Book III I found it to be perfunctory and somehow I felt this itch to rush Book III, I am really not a fan of history especially when its all about wars, plebs in wars, horses in wars, generals in wars, and other stuff in wars -- which was what Book III was all about yet there are words of sagacity in Book III, a lot of them, which you can prepare a highlighter for. It is noteworthy that The Discourses is filled with wisdom, psychology, and political theories, but it become more lengthy because of the Titus Levy's historical accounts which Machiavelli adduced in his discourses. I might say that about 70% of the The Discourses is history.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6446479379011433800" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


