<div id="review_672249522" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/672249522" />
    <a title="Kamrud Jacobson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16977873-kamrud-jacobson"><img alt="Kamrud Jacobson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1359580703p2/16977873.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/672249522?book_show_action=true">Jan 28, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kamrud Jacobson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kamrud Jacobson" href="/user/show/16977873-kamrud-jacobson">Kamrud Jacobson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer672249522" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9737429217187931459">Machiavelli is one of those thinkers who is both ahead of his time in terms of his understanding human nature and realist political theory AND a product of his time. <br/><br/>His writing in this book far surpasses his often misunderstood work, &quot;The prince&quot; in its clear eyed and unapologitic look at political reality. More than that his observations on human nature and ambition are truly timeless. His thoughts on power and its roles and uses reads like the type of thing Amereicans would be declaring three</span>
  <span id="freeText9737429217187931459" style="display:none">Machiavelli is one of those thinkers who is both ahead of his time in terms of his understanding human nature and realist political theory AND a product of his time. <br /><br />His writing in this book far surpasses his often misunderstood work, "The prince" in its clear eyed and unapologitic look at political reality. More than that his observations on human nature and ambition are truly timeless. His thoughts on power and its roles and uses reads like the type of thing Amereicans would be declaring three centuries later. So many of his comments are applicable to the current world that it seems almost plageristic to hear more recent authors stating their own conclusions about political theory when Machiavelli said it first.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9737429217187931459" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


